2026-04-16 12:41:44 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal 10 kΩ sensor‑bias / reference resistor network (misdesign: used as sole ground return for relay output and load path)'] hypothesis_explanation='All hardware elements tested so far (battery, PSU wiring, relay coil/driver, relay contacts, PCB traces to external + and − terminals, indicator and load module wiring, and load‑module diode) behave nominal. Yet the control‑module output never rises above ~0.36 V despite 12 V at the relay input and confirmed continuity from relay output to the external + terminal. The internal reference node of the ambient sensor module sits about 11.87 V above PSU −, with ~11.87 V across a measured 10 kΩ resistor and ~1.19 mA current; this resistor is the only intentional connection between the module’s internal ground network and true 0 V. Because the relay output and external + line are referenced to this floating internal node through the same ground network, the entire output path is returned to the battery negative only through 10 kΩ. That makes the path unable to deliver appreciable current to the load; instead, the load and any indicator LEDs form a divider against the 10 kΩ bias resistor, clamping the ‘+’ output to a small value (~0.12–0.36 V), exactly what is observed. This is not a broken trace or bad contact but a design/configuration fault: the 10 kΩ sensor‑bias / reference resistor network is incorrectly being used as the only ground return for the power path that should feed the external load. Correct behavior would require the relay output/load return to connect directly to PSU −, with the 10 kΩ only biasing the sensor/comparator. Therefore the root cause is the mis‑implemented 10 kΩ reference network inside the ambient sensor module, which keeps the module’s output floating through a high resistance instead of referencing it properly to ground, preventing the lamp from ever receiving 12 V and producing the very small voltages measured at the module output and at the load.'
