2026-04-16 12:42:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contact orientation / wiring at low side (relay output incorrectly tied to − rail instead of + path)', 'ambient sensor module PCB wiring of relay contacts relative to external + and − output terminals'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show: (1) the PSU provides a solid 12 V. (2) The relay input terminal sits at ~11.99 V relative to PSU −, correctly connected to PSU +. (3) The other side of the same relay contact—the so‑called “relay output” that should feed the control module’s + output cable—is instead sitting at ~0.36 V above PSU −. (4) The control module’s external + output cable and the load module input + are also at ~0.36 V, while their − lines are at 0 V. (5) Only about 0.36 V appears across the load‑input diode and across the module’s output terminals. There is a solid 10 kΩ bias to ground used by the sensor, but no low‑resistance return path from the 0.36 V node to 0 V other than through that bias network.\n\nThese facts imply that the relay is not actually placing the 11.99 V node onto the output rail at all. Instead, the contact that is supposed to connect PSU + to the output is wired so that its moving arm is tied to the low side / ground side of the circuit (or to a node near ground), and the supposedly high “relay input” terminal is fixed at 12 V but never switched to the output. When the relay closes, the arm shorts the output node toward the low‑side network, leaving it at only a few hundred millivolts above 0 V (set by leakage through the 10 kΩ sensor‑bias path and other internal loads). That explains why only ~0.36 V is ever available at the control output, the indicator LED never sees full forward bias, and the lamp and its internal indicator are always off, regardless of potentiometer settings.\n\nTherefore the fault is not in the coil drive, the 10 kΩ reference, or the external cabling, but in how the relay contacts are wired on the PCB: the contact terminals have been mis‑routed or swapped so that the output is effectively tied toward the − rail rather than to the +12 V rail when closed. Repairing the PCB wiring of the relay contacts so that one fixed contact is on PSU + and the moving contact feeds the external + output / indicator LED should restore full 12 V to the load and correct the behavior.'
