2026-04-16 12:42:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module positive output cable connection at control-module input (+) terminal', 'ambient sensor module external + input terminal / mating connector'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal circuitry in the ambient sensor module, including relay, reference network, PCB traces, and wiring to the output, has repeatedly tested good. The module’s relay input node is at ~12 V relative to PSU −, and there is direct continuity (≈0.2 Ω) between the relay input and the PSU Output Cable (+). Yet, when measuring at the ambient sensor module “output” side and at the load input, only ~0.36 V is present, and the whole downstream path (including the internal reference node via a 10 kΩ bias resistor) floats around this same ≈0.12–0.36 V above true ground.\n\nThese data imply that 12 V from the PSU is not actually being delivered into the ambient sensor module’s internal + rail; instead, the relay and internal logic are being powered from a local 12 V node that is not the same node as the external + input wiring used for the output path. The only remaining place a disconnection can exist without affecting all the previously tested internal circuits is at the interface between the PSU positive cable and the ambient sensor module’s + input connector itself: a poor or intermittent mechanical contact, partially mated terminal, or cracked solder joint right at that external + input pad can leave the external cable at 12 V while the module’s internal + bus is effectively open. The small ~0.36 V observed at the module outputs then results from leakage/bias currents through the 10 kΩ reference network and other high‑impedance paths, not from a solid 12 V feed.\n\nTherefore the most probable root cause is a faulty connection at the power supply module positive output cable into the ambient sensor module’s + input terminal (or the mating connector on the sensor module), leaving the control and load path effectively unpowered even though the PSU itself is good and all internal sensor‑module components are intact.'
