2026-04-16 12:42:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module negative output cable connection at control‑module input (−) terminal', 'ambient sensor module external − input terminal / mating connector', 'ambient sensor module external − output terminal / mating connector', 'interconnecting cable used for the − rail between power supply, sensor module, and load'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal circuitry modules, relay contacts, bias network, and PCB traces have repeatedly tested nominal. We always measure a solid ~12 V from PSU + to PSU −, and ~12 V from PSU + to the relay input. However, downstream of the control module and at the load we only ever see about 0.36 V between the supposed + and − rails, while the internal sensor reference node floats about 0.12–0.36 V above the conductor that the multimeter sees as 0 V.\n\nThis pattern is consistent with the main current return (− rail) to the load path being effectively open or extremely high impedance outside the control module: a break or poor contact in the negative interconnection cabling or its mating terminals. Internally, the sensor circuitry references ground through the 10 kΩ bias resistor, so in the absence of a solid external − connection the module and its output nodes float near the sensor bias potential (~0.12–0.36 V). That explains why:\n- PSU module shows correct 12 V and LED, proving its internal − is intact.\n- Inside the control module we can reference signals to PSU − and get correct 12 V on the relay input, but when measuring at the external output pair or at the load the apparent supply collapses to a few hundred millivolts because the return path is open.\n- Replacing internal control‑module paths has had no effect, and visual checks showed correct polarity but do not guarantee crimp/spring contact integrity.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a faulty connection in the external negative rail between modules—specifically the − cable or its plug/socket at the control‑module input or output, or the single − interconnect cable that links these modules. Repairing or replacing these connectors/cables should restore a solid 0 V reference to the sensor and load, allowing the relay output to actually deliver 12 V across the load and eliminating the abnormal low‑voltage measurements and lamp malfunction.'
