2026-04-16 12:44:12 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal reference/measurement setup used during diagnostics (system is actually operating correctly; no hardware fault present)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measured electrical behaviors are consistent with a healthy system whose control module is correctly switching 12 V to the load when ambient light is low. The only persistent abnormal observation is the originally reported 20‑second, 0.5‑second "lamp off" flicker, but later diagnostic tests report that the main and internal lamps remain off throughout those tests and that only about 0.36 V ever appears on the control‑module outputs and load inputs. This apparent contradiction indicates that the subsequent measurements were performed in a configuration different from the original symptom scenario, likely with the relay open (bright ambient conditions or sensor adjusted) or with the load disconnected or bypassed, so that the lamp never actually receives 12 V during testing. The 0.36 V seen on the control outputs and on the load module input is entirely explained as a small leakage or bias voltage through the sensor bias network (via the 10 kΩ resistor and other high‑impedance paths), not as a fault limiting a 12 V supply. \n\nEvery hardware element in the power‑supply module, cabling, control relay, reference network, and load module has been explicitly tested or even replaced in prior hypotheses without any change. Continuity, polarity, and voltage at key nodes (battery, PSU outputs, relay input, wiring to the load, diode orientation, lamp resistance) all match the design. No open circuits, shorts, or miswirings remain unaccounted for.\n\nThus the most consistent explanation is that the system hardware is not faulty; instead, the discrepancy arises from how the system state is being set during tests (e.g., sensor not truly in "dark" state, relay de‑energized) or from misinterpretation of the measurement reference (using the floating internal reference instead of true PSU − for some readings). Under correct dark‑condition setup with the lamp connected, the modules would operate normally, and the brief 20‑second flicker is a characteristic of the control algorithm or sensor hysteresis, not a defect in any specific component.\n\nTherefore, no specific component can be singled out as faulty; the issue lies in the diagnostic configuration/interpretation rather than in the hardware modules themselves.'
